BOUGHT WITH THE INCOME FROM THE SAGE ENDOWMENT FUND THE GIFT OP 1891 feg. y^.i^/j^/^f<a3i. 5474 The d^te shows when this volume was taken. T<i renew this book copy the call No. and give to the librarian. — HOME USE RULES. All Boolcs subject to Recall. Books not used for instruction or researcli are returnable within 4 weeks. Volumes of periodi cals and of pampiilets are held in the library as much as possible. For special purposes they are given out for a limited time. Borrowers should not use their library privileges- for , the bene- fit Of other persons. Books not needed during recess periods should be returned to the library, or arrange- ments made for their return during borrow- er's absence, if wanted. Books needed by more than one person are held on the reserve list. B o ok s of special value and gift books, when the giver wishes it, are not allowed to circulate. Readers are asked to report all cases of books marked or mutilated. Do not deface books by marks and writing. CORNELL UNIVERSITY UBRARY 924 091 890 818 The original of this book is in the Cornell University Library. There are no known copyright restrictions in the United States on the use of the text. http://www.archive.org/details/cu31924091890818 THE NEW VOLUMES OF THE ENCYCLOPAEDIA BRITANNICA An INDEX TO THE COMPLETE Encyclopedia Britannica BEING THE ELEVENTH OF THE NEW VOLUMES WHICH CONSTITUTE IN CONJUNCTION WITH THE EXISTING VOLUMES OF THE NINTH EDITION THE TENTH EDITION OF THAT WORK VOLUME XXXV OF THE COMPLETE WORK PUBLISHED BY ADAM & CHARLES . ' THE TIMES ' . . BLACK, EDINBURGH PRINTING HOUSE & LONDON . . . SQUARE, LONDON MCMIII EDITOEIAL NOTE AT the conclusion of their work, the Editors desire to express their hearty apprecia- tion of the valuable assistance rendered to them throughout the three and a half years of its progress by many eminent authorities, in addition to the invariable considera- tion and the loyal co-operation which they have received at ,the hands of the Departmental Editors and the contributors. In organizing and editing a work of the magnitude of the EncyclopoBdia Britannica, and endeavouring to maintain in this further instalment the standard of preceding editions, it was necessary to frequently call in the aid not only of experts who could give special advice on technical details, but also of experienced men of affairs, whose judgment served to fortify ^that of the Editors themselves in the re- sponsible task to which they were committed. Such advice and help have always been most willingly and generously given. It is impossible to describe here the different occasions on which such services were required, and to give the names of all those who have rendered them ; but the Editors cannot close this record of their labours without acknowledging in this brief form their indebtedness in this respect to a wide circle of amid curiae, among whom may be specially mentioned the Lord Chancellor (Earl of Halsbury), Lord Kelvin, the late Lord Acton, the late Bishop Creighton, Lord Eayleigh, Lord Roberts, Lord Wolseley, Lord Reay, the Japanese Minister in London (Viscount Hayashi), Sir W. S. Church, Bart. (President of the College of Physicians), the late Sir William MacCormao, Bart. (President of the College of Surgeons), Sir W. T. Thiselton Dyer (Director of the Royal Gardens, Kew), Sir George Birdwood, Sir J. G." Fitch, the Rev. Dr. T. Fowler (President of C.C.C, Oxford), Professor Thomas Case, the late Sir W. Priestley, Dr. Ray Lankester (Director of the National History Museum, South Kensington), Sir Frederick Pollock, Bart., Mr. Henry Gannett of the Geological Survey, Washington, Professor W. C. Unwin (who arranged with the writers of the articles on engineering), Mr. Everard Green (Rouge Dragon), the Hon. Valentine Bell, Dr. T. Leal, Mr. John Murray. The Editors also thank those owners of pictures who kindly allowed reproductions to be given, and the various publishers and newspaper editors and proprietors who have freely allowed the use of material of which they held the copyright. EXPLANATOEY NOTE FIGURES printed in bold face type (e.g. 29) refer to the number of the volume, those in light face type {e.g. 375) refer to the number of the page, and the letters a and b, c and d to the upper and lower halves of the left and right hand columns of the page respectively. In the case, however, of references to Volume 34 (the Atlas Volume) the first number in light face type refers, not to the number of the page, but to the number of the map. For example, the entry " Sedal 34 20 E5 " shows that in Volume 34 map 20 contains the name Sedai, and that Sedal lies in the vertical division E and the horizontal division 5. An entry thus : 29 xiv, refers to the 14th page of the introductory essay to the 29th Volume. A rule or dash denotes a repetition of the preceding index-word. In the case of compound names printed without a hyphen, it denotes the repetition of the first word only, e.g. : — Caesarea Augusta 24 770c. — Philippi 4- 640a. The prefix St (Saint) and the articles Le and La, however, have been treated as inseparable from the word which they precede ; here, therefore, the rule denotes the repetition of both words, e.g. La Vega, F. 11 724b. St Albans : town, Me., U.S. 34 65 E6. — , town, N.S.W. 34 51 J4. R. de 32 764a Surnames of foreigners beginning with the prefixes shown below have been indexed as indicated by these instances : — Del Rio has been indexed under Del. D'Abbadie has been indexed under Abbadie. Delia Cassa „ Delia. Da Silva Silva. • Des Cloiseaux „ Des. De Croitrai „ Croitrai. Du Blois Du. De La Place „ La Place. La Condamine „ La. Von Humboldt „ Humboldt Le Sage „ tr\Tfari-vckCs nil /^ ctt-\r\ Le. Van Beneden „ ■^r»Q ■mTvrA/-\c'/:» r\+ n \ -r\\r\ n r\i r^'i'-i rrn-i-t rv-n Beneden. if they were written Mac and Saint. For the purpose of difi"erentiation, the word town is used in this index to describe any inhabited spot, irrespective of its size or importance. ABBREVIATIONS USED IN INDEX 